Comparing State School Performance with State Crime Rates¶

Rachel Roberts and Shayne Shelton

Github Link

Datasets¶

State Crime Dataset:

Dataset in CSV format containing crime reports spanning from 1960 to 2019. Data is divided into two main categories: property and violent crime. Property crime includes things such as burglary, larceny, and motor related crime. Violent crime refers to assault, murder, rape, and robbery.

State School Performance Data Set:

Robust dataset in CSV format containing various statistics relating to state school performance from 2005 up until 2015. It contains avergae GPA and SAT scores by state as well as separations by subject and income level. For example, data contains the average GPA of all students in this state during a certain year in Math, or average SAT score for students with a family income between 60-80k.

State Government Finances:

The Annual Survey of State Government Finances provides a comprehensive summary of the annual survey findings for state governments, as well as data for individual states. The data contain detail of revenue by source, expenditure by object and function, indebtedness by term, and assets by purpose. This data goes back for almost two decades across every date. (1992 - 2019)

Research Questions and Discussion¶

We intend to use these datasets to explore how factors like Average GPA or SAT score for each state are related with state crime rates. For example, answering questions such as do states that have a higher average GPA have lower crime rates? Once we analyze whether there is a correlation between different types of crime rate and school performance metrics, we want to incroporate the state government finance dataset to perform deeper analyses such as:

Do states that have higher expenditure towards education have higher average GPAs/test scores?

Do states that have higher expenditure towards law enforcement have lower crime rates?

Using these results, we hope to gain a better insight on how allocating governement spending can influence school performance and crime rates.

We first want to explore the relationship between state school performance metrics and state crime rates, and then explore whether investing in education is a potential way to lower crime rates based on this relationship.

Additional Extraction, Transform, and Load (ETL) + Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)¶

To get a better idea of what the general trends in our school performance dataset are, we will begin by calculating the average subject GPAs across all the years present in the data set (2006-2015) and creating a vizualization. This will help us see which states on average have higher GPAs in the different subject areas each year.

Average English GPA for each State

In [16]:
# Filter the DataFrame to include only rows where Variable is 'Academic Subjects.English.Average GPA'
english_gpa_df = school_scores_tidy[school_scores_tidy['Variable'] == 'Academic Subjects.English.Average GPA']

# Pivot the filtered DataFrame to have years as columns and English GPA as values
df_pivot = english_gpa_df.pivot_table(index='State.Name', columns='Year', values='Value', aggfunc='mean')

# Calculate the average GPA for all years for each state, skipping NaN values
df_pivot['Average_GPA_All_Years'] = df_pivot.mean(axis=1, skipna=True)

# Extract only the columns 'State.Name' and 'Average_GPA_All_Years'
average_englishgpa_by_state = df_pivot[['Average_GPA_All_Years']]

# Sort the DataFrame by the average GPA in descending order
average_englishgpa_by_state.sort_values(by='Average_GPA_All_Years', ascending=False, inplace=True)

# Display the DataFrame
average_englishgpa_by_state.head()

import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from sklearn.preprocessing import MinMaxScaler

# Normalize the violent crime rates and average math GPA
scaler = MinMaxScaler()
normalized_crime_rate = scaler.fit_transform(average_vrates_by_state.values.reshape(-1, 1)) # Reshape for MinMaxScaler
normalized_mgpa = scaler.fit_transform(average_mgpa_by_state.values.reshape(-1, 1)) # Reshape for MinMaxScaler

# Create DataFrames for the normalized data
normalized_crime_rate_df = pd.DataFrame(normalized_crime_rate, index=average_vrates_by_state.index, columns=['Normalized Crime Rate'])
normalized_mgpa_df = pd.DataFrame(normalized_mgpa, index=average_mgpa_by_state.index, columns=['Normalized Math GPA'])

# Perform inner join to retain only states present in both datasets
normalized_data = pd.merge(normalized_crime_rate_df, normalized_mgpa_df, left_index=True, right_index=True)

plt.figure(figsize=(15, 12))

plt.scatter(normalized_data['Normalized Math GPA'], normalized_data['Normalized Crime Rate'])

for i, state in enumerate(normalized_data.index):
    plt.annotate(state, (normalized_data['Normalized Math GPA'].iloc[i], normalized_data['Normalized Crime Rate'].iloc[i]), fontsize=10)

plt.xlabel('Normalized Math GPA')
plt.ylabel('Normalized Violent Crime Rate')
plt.title('Normalized Average Math GPA vs Violent Crime Rate by State')
plt.grid(True)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Overall, there is not a strong correlation between the different average subject GPAs with violent or property crime rates. Averaging all the GPAs across all the years in the dataset and doing the same with the state crime dataset might be too broad to pick up on relationships between the data.

Our next step is to take a closer look by analyzing the Louisiana data specifically.

import pandas as pd
import numpy as np

# take our array of total crime rates is named 'total_crime_rates'
total_crime_rates = np.array([4293., 4802., 4945.1, 4552.3, 4485.6, 4200.1, 4238.5, 4037.5, 4100.5, 3973.5, 3893.1])

# Create a new DataFrame containing the years 2005-2015
years = range(2005, 2016)
sc_t_filtered = pd.DataFrame({'Year': years})

# Add the 'Total Crime Rate' column to the DataFrame
sc_t_filtered['Total Crime Rate'] = total_crime_rates

# Merge with with filtered English GPA DF'
